Syntax













句法學
Syntax    Course details (102)


This course introduces students to syntactic theory ‒ the study of the structure of sentences and the properties these structures have. 
The focus will be on treatments of syntax involving Optimality Theory (OT), a theory involving linguistic constraints that conflict with one another, 
and competition among linguistic expressions to satisfy these constraints. The first half of the course will introduce basic concepts of syntactic theory: 
what the goals are, what data we wish to analyze, how the data is collected, what constitutes scientifically adequate analysis, what such an analysis could look like, 
and what OT-based syntactic analyses look like.
   
The second half of the course will focus on a particular topic each week, and an OT based analysis of the topic under discussion. 




There are four main goals of this course:



Introduce students to the use of the scientific method in the study of language.




Introduce students to theoretical syntax, the study of sentence formation, one of the two major branches of linguistics.




Introduce students to OT approaches to linguistic data, especially in syntax.




Bolster students’ analytical skills, especially through applying familiar concepts to unfamiliar data.












